	<item>
		<title>What Is Competitive Positioning? (+How to Create Yours)</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/competitive-positioning</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[John Shieldsmith]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 30 Jul 2024 14:52:58 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Business Planning & Strategy]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/?p=84676</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Use this guide to competitive positioning to show the world why your business is unique.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/competitive-positioning">What Is Competitive Positioning? (+How to Create Yours)</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>You likely set out to start your company because you have something to offer‚Äîsomething that makes you, your product, and your company different from the rest. It‚Äôs ultimately this difference, not your product or service, that you sell. This is easier said than done unless you master your competitive positioning.</p>
<p>Before diving into finding your competitive positioning and learning how to sell your ‚Äúdifference,‚Äù it‚Äôs important to understand what competitive positioning is. Then, we can crack the code on your differences and streamline things with a template.</p>
<h3>Contents</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#what-is-competitive-positioning">What is competitive positioning?</a></li>
<li><a href="#why-does-competitive-positioning-matter">Why does competitive positioning matter?</a></li>
<li><a href="#5-tips-to-find-your-competitive-positioning">5 tips to find your competitive positioning</a></li>
<li><a href="#what-is-a-competitive-positioning-map">What is a competitive positioning map?</a></li>
<li><a href="#your-competitive-positioning-map">Competitive positioning map example</a></li>
</ul>
<div id="what-is-competitive-positioning"></div>
<h2>What is competitive positioning?</h2>
<p>Every successful company has a differentiator that makes them competitive. Competitive positioning is how you market your company to ensure it stands apart from the competition and leverages its strengths.</p>
<p>Competitive positioning ultimately comes down to marketing, branding, and how you talk about your business and your products or services. Even if you‚Äôre in a similar space as other businesses, the right competitive positioning will help you stand apart and drive your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/unique-selling-proposition">unique selling proposition</a>.</p>
<p>Several elements typically go into competitive positioning, including:</p>
<ul>
<li>The competition and your strengths and weaknesses</li>
<li>Your product‚Äôs value</li>
<li>Market likes and dislikes for competitor products or services</li>
<li>Market likes and dislikes for your products or services</li>
<li>Pricing and market trends</li>
</ul>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f575.png" alt="üïµ" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Want to see how successful your competitor‚Äôs search ads are?</strong> Download this free <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/resources/google-ads-industry-benchmarks?cid=Web_WS_InContent_Guide_2024GoogleAdsBenchmarks_Download">Google Ads Industry Benchmark Report</a>.</p>
<div id="why-does-competitive-positioning-matter"></div>
<h2>Why does competitive positioning matter?</h2>
<p><a href="https://www.bls.gov/bdm/us_age_naics_00_table7.txt" target="_blank" rel="noopener">50%</a> of businesses fail by their fifth year. There are many reasons businesses fail, but a lack of competitive positioning is a big one. After all, if you can‚Äôt express why your products are better and different than the competition‚Äôs, how will a customer ever make that choice?</p>
<p>Once you have it nailed down, competitive positioning:</p>
<ul>
<li>Differentiates your brand and attracts customers in your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/05/11/target-audience">target audience</a>.</li>
<li>Helps you effectively speak to <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/types-of-customer-needs/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">customer pain points</a> and problems.</li>
<li>Informs your branding and marketing.</li>
<li>Allows you to create a more insightful <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/09/19/customer-journey-map-templates">customer journey</a>.</li>
<li>Makes building <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2015/07/10/brand-awareness">brand awareness</a> much easier.</li>
</ul>
<p>The perks of competitive positioning can be summed up by part of the name itself: competitive. Ultimately, when you‚Äôre confident in your competitive positioning, you‚Äôre signaling to potential customers and other brands that you‚Äôre confident in whatever you‚Äôre selling. And this is how you stay competitive.</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f44b.png" alt="üëã" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Free download &gt;&gt;</strong> <a href="https://marketing.localiq.com/WSLIQContentDLTheDefinitiveGuideBrandAwareness.html?cid=Web_WS_InContent_BrandAwareness_Guide_Download">The Definitive Guide to Brand Awareness: Top Strategies, Examples, &amp; How to Measure Success</a>.</p>
<div id="5-tips-to-find-your-competitive-positioning"></div>
<h2>5 tips to find your competitive positioning</h2>
<p>You probably won‚Äôt find your competitive positioning overnight, and it may even change over time. These tips will help you find your competitive positioning now and stay on top of it as it evolves.</p>
<h3>1. Ensure you know the market</h3>
<p>First and foremost, you need to know where you fit in the market.</p>
<p>Start by running a market analysis. Review the landscape and note how many competitors are out there, what the potential market size and customer base look like, and what the average revenue is for businesses in this space. It‚Äôs also not a bad idea to conduct a tried-and-true <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/03/16/marketing-competitive-analysis#_ga=2.182940582.1090122938.1698345807-369991937.1695347762&amp;_gac=1.158025416.1695698446.CjwKCAjw38SoBhB6EiwA8EQVLu7t5v3dzfKLQDhndyDc4IcBctoDyLNeIkf8BMcvXfejZz5caP-EUBoCAG4QAvD_BwE">SWOT analysis</a>.</p>
<p><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/competitive-positioning-wordstream-swot.webp" alt="competitive positioning - swot analysis chart." width="787" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-84678 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/competitive-positioning-wordstream-swot.webp 787w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/competitive-positioning-wordstream-swot-480x366.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 787px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>This is also a good time to start thinking about your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2015/09/23/buyer-personas">ideal customer persona</a> (ICP). Who is your ideal customer? What are their likes and dislikes? What are their major pain points? What about your product or service would appeal to them?</p>
<p>If your business is already off the ground, consider <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/customer-feedback-questions/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">polling your current customers</a> to gain useful insights grounded in reality.</p>
<h3>2. Perform in-depth competitor research</h3>
<p><a href="https://localiq.com/blog/why-is-it-important-companies-have-competitors/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Knowing your competitors</a> is as important as knowing your own company and market, if not more.</p>
<p>Perform in-depth competitor research to find out:</p>
<ul>
<li>Who are the biggest competitors in your space?</li>
<li>What do their customers like about their offerings?</li>
<li>What are the biggest customer complaints about their offerings?</li>
<li>Are there any gaps your product or services fill or could fill?</li>
</ul>
<p>During this phase, pay special attention to customer complaints and any gaps you find. If the majority of competitors are receiving similar complaints about a product or a lack of an offering, this is a golden opportunity for you.</p>
<p>For example, say you run an online shoe store. If your direct competitors are all receiving negative marks about their return policy, you could position yourself as the ‚Äúcustomer-centric‚Äù shoe store and offer a better return policy with a free trial period.</p>
<h3>3. List out your objectives</h3>
<p>Your positioning isn‚Äôt only affected by your company‚Äôs current status but also by your future plans and objectives. This is especially the case when fulfilling your objectives could result in your company pivoting in a big way.</p>
<p>For example, if your quarterly goal is to launch two marketing campaigns, this isn‚Äôt necessarily a pivotal moment for your company. If you have a fiscal year goal of launching a new product, that is something you should factor into your positioning.</p>
<p>Gather any relevant stakeholders and list out all your short and long-term goals and objectives. Then, review the list and determine which ones have the potential to impact your company‚Äôs positioning. Take note of these goals and factor them in as you move forward with the rest of this guide.</p>
<h3>4. Lean into your niche</h3>
<p>A core part of determining what makes you competitive is finding your niche and leaning in on it as much as possible.</p>
<p>Start by reflecting on your<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/competitive-analysis"> competitive analysis</a> and your own products and positioning. Then, think about your key differences and list them.</p>
<p>Next, list every problem your target audience has that you intend to solve. Be realistic and only call attention to problems you can solve in the near future without any significant funding or company overhaul.</p>
<p>With your competitor knowledge and list of target problems, now it‚Äôs time to identify what makes you different. Figure this out by answering the following questions in as much detail as you can:</p>
<ul>
<li>What are the problems only you can solve?</li>
<li>What is your company strongest at?</li>
<li>What gaps can you realistically fill?</li>
</ul>
<p>Answering the above questions will ultimately help you determine your niche‚Äîthe position only your company and product(s) can fill.</p>
<h3>5. Use gaps to define your competitive positioning</h3>
<p>Once you understand your customers and competitors, it‚Äôs time to use that knowledge to position your brand and products competitively.</p>
<p>You do that by looking for gaps in customer needs that your competitors don‚Äôt fulfill.</p>
<p>Here‚Äôs an example. Let‚Äôs say all of your competitors provide a luxury experience at premium prices that solve the needs of high-income clients. In your customer research, you‚Äôve identified a large segment of buyers who don‚Äôt use their service because of the price point but would if it were more accessible. So, you design a simplified ‚Äúno frills‚Äù version and capture an underserved pool of eager buyers.</p>
<div id="what-is-a-competitive-positioning-map"></div>
<h2>What is a competitive positioning map?</h2>
<p>A competitive positioning map is a graph that positions competitors along two variables. It‚Äôs designed to help you visualize gaps in the market for those two characteristics.</p>
<p>Creating a competitive positioning map is a three-step process:</p>
<ol>
<li>Pick two variables, like cost (high vs. low), service level (self-serve vs. concierge), or features (full-feature vs. simple design).</li>
<li>Plot where each of your competitors falls for each of those two variables.</li>
<li>¬†Look for the gaps in service.</li>
</ol>
<div id="your-competitive-positioning-map"></div>
<h2>Competitive positioning map example</h2>
<p>Here&#8217;s an example of a competitive positioning map you can use to create your own.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/competitive-positioning-wordstream-map.webp" alt="competitive positioning - Template of a competitive positioning map" width="936" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-84679 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/competitive-positioning-wordstream-map.webp 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/competitive-positioning-wordstream-map-480x308.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<h2>Competitive positioning is a process, not a conclusion</h2>
<p>As you embark on your competitive journey, keep in mind your positioning is unlikely to be set in stone. Audience likes and dislikes change, competitors rebrand and launch new products, and your own products and branding can evolve. Because of this, it‚Äôs a good idea to reevaluate your competitive positioning every year or anytime you have a major brand or product overhaul.</p>
<p>While you won‚Äôt find your competitive positioning overnight, the aforementioned steps will get you well on your way to knowing where your company stands in the market‚Äîa major step toward long-term success.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/competitive-positioning">What Is Competitive Positioning? (+How to Create Yours)</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
